WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.280
Thanks everyone for joining. I hope this is going to be an interesting session. I'll

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:20.520
do my best at least. So what I'm going to speak about is building a medical device with

00:00:20.520 --> 00:00:26.520
R. But before I sort of go into what a medical device is, I want to briefly explain what

00:00:26.520 --> 00:00:36.480
we actually do. So I work at a company called InsightRx and we build a medical device as

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:48.000
you would have guessed. But to go into what we're actually building, let's say, and let's

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:53.959
hope it won't happen, but let's say you have to go into the hospital for maybe an infection

00:00:53.959 --> 00:01:02.680
or something, you will get a dose of a drug. But you have to realize that dose is often

00:01:02.680 --> 00:01:12.199
developed based on a sort of average of a population. And it might not actually be the

00:01:12.199 --> 00:01:17.080
best dose for you as an individual because you might be sort of on one of the extremes

00:01:17.080 --> 00:01:25.720
of that in terms of the pharmacology. Now this is especially important for drugs like

00:01:25.720 --> 00:01:32.720
antibiotics, chemotherapy and transplantation drugs. And especially if you're very young,

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:38.639
if you're very old or if you're very sick, this is actually very important to get the

00:01:38.639 --> 00:01:46.279
right dose for you as an individual. Now if we have some information about you, let's

00:01:46.279 --> 00:01:57.080
say you have the weight, the height, the age of you, and we know the history of all

00:01:57.080 --> 00:02:04.000
the drugs that you took. We measured the concentration of drug in your body and perhaps some other

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:13.199
biomarkers and maybe we even have some genomic data from you. That can actually help to inform

00:02:13.279 --> 00:02:22.720
you about what you should actually receive in terms of a drug dose. And we use that data to

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:35.039
update our models, the pharmacology models that we use. And we use Bayesian updating to actually

00:02:35.039 --> 00:02:46.960
get to what would be the optimal choice for you as an individual. Now we wrap this framework. We

00:02:46.960 --> 00:02:52.559
built a cloud-based web application around this framework based again on those pharmacology

00:02:52.559 --> 00:02:57.919
models. So it's not like a machine learning black box that we don't know what's going on. This is

00:02:57.919 --> 00:03:04.679
all grounded in pharmacology. And the last thing I want to highlight here is that it's

00:03:04.679 --> 00:03:12.639
integrated into the clinical workflow. So the intended users here will mostly be pharmacists,

00:03:12.639 --> 00:03:21.600
but also we have a few doctors that are using the platform. Now to get back to the medical device

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:28.639
part, what is a medical device? Well, we all know that this and this and this is a medical device,

00:03:29.080 --> 00:03:40.520
but in this talk, I'm going to focus on what is software as a medical device. And more specifically,

00:03:40.520 --> 00:03:48.880
I'm going to talk about clinical decision support tools. If you decide to build a medical device,

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:54.919
most likely you will go through the following stages. We're in the pre-development stage.

00:03:55.080 --> 00:04:00.800
You basically decide which class of medical device you're going to be, what are the claims

00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:07.320
you are making. And this is also the stage where you set up a quality system. And then in the next

00:04:07.320 --> 00:04:13.880
stage, you'll begin development of your products under design controls and the quality system that

00:04:13.880 --> 00:04:22.399
you developed. And then in later stages, you'll apply the verification framework that you set up.

00:04:22.399 --> 00:04:30.760
And then before you file with the FDA, you do some validation with actual users. And then you

00:04:30.760 --> 00:04:39.959
should be good to release this into the wild. I would say the most important thing in this

00:04:39.959 --> 00:04:49.359
whole process is probably the risk analysis that you will do. You'll do that really early on. And

00:04:49.720 --> 00:04:56.399
in this case, you scope out what are all the risks associated with the medical device. And once you

00:04:56.399 --> 00:05:04.880
have that, you can actually develop a document called the software specifications. And that is

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:13.519
just a long list of things like the software shall be able to do this and that basically 100 times

00:05:13.600 --> 00:05:22.920
or more. So all these requirements, what you can do then is map these to actual verification steps.

00:05:22.920 --> 00:05:36.720
So what that means in practice, you actually write out a specific requirement as a scenario in code.

00:05:36.720 --> 00:05:46.279
And then you'll basically run through all these verification steps. So if you speak about the web

00:05:46.279 --> 00:05:54.600
app as a whole, what you usually use for that is, for example, a tool like Selenium. But in the

00:05:54.600 --> 00:06:00.480
context of the conference here, I'm going to speak mostly about the API, because that's the part

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:11.519
what's written in R. And for that, mainly for the unit test, we use test that, as I'm sure a lot of

00:06:11.519 --> 00:06:17.600
you are also using. But I want to focus on one other thing here is that what we developed in-house,

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:30.160
which is a package called JSON2 test. And what that package specifically is doing is, oh, I also

00:06:30.160 --> 00:06:38.799
want to refer here to the talk yesterday by Alice Huge, which was a very interesting talk, more or

00:06:38.799 --> 00:06:45.440
less about the same thing here. But going into the package where we developed, what the package does

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:52.760
is, because if you remember all the requirements that we had to write down and to write out as code,

00:06:52.760 --> 00:06:58.720
instead of writing these all out as code, as a specific scenario to walk through, we actually

00:06:58.760 --> 00:07:11.320
record the API payloads that are being sent from the web app, and then write a document that

00:07:11.320 --> 00:07:16.799
basically specifies what we expect that API load to be. And then we compare it with the actual API

00:07:16.799 --> 00:07:23.959
output. So instead of writing all these tests, we use a package to actually do it for us. So that has

00:07:23.959 --> 00:07:32.040
helped us to implement this a lot faster than we would otherwise have been able to do. So this

00:07:32.040 --> 00:07:42.279
package is also available in this link. It's not yet on CRAN. So that's more or less what I want

00:07:42.279 --> 00:07:52.000
to say about the validation, the verification steps that are required. But I also want to go

00:07:52.000 --> 00:08:03.320
into more about what other things are required. So what you also find in the regulatory documents

00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:08.359
is a lot of stuff about security, privacy, stability, and things like that. But once you

00:08:08.359 --> 00:08:15.119
go speaking to clients, there will also be other requirements. Of course, clients also have a lot

00:08:15.119 --> 00:08:25.600
of requirements about security and privacy, et cetera. But they also want you to have a nice

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:34.320
product, a good UI, UX. It has to be fast. So like I said, the end user of our products are clinicians.

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:44.000
They won't have the time to wait for half an hour for those advice. So it has to be there very

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:53.080
quickly. So then we can go into some of the choices that we made and what we developed. And

00:08:53.080 --> 00:08:59.239
the first thing here is the computations. And like I said in the introduction, we use

00:08:59.239 --> 00:09:07.880
pharmacology models. And those are often defined as differential equations. And when we started

00:09:07.880 --> 00:09:15.080
out five years ago, there was not really a package or anything in R to actually handle

00:09:15.080 --> 00:09:25.080
that. So that's why we wrote a package called PKPDSim. And the main thing that it's doing,

00:09:25.080 --> 00:09:32.280
it can do a prediction of the concentration of a specific drug in the body over time.

00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:40.479
That's basically the core of our platform. Again, this is also open source. It's open source

00:09:40.479 --> 00:09:54.840
available. And the lesson that we learned here over time is that, well, at first, it took a lot

00:09:54.840 --> 00:10:00.640
of work to actually implement this ourself. But over time, we realized that this actually has

00:10:00.640 --> 00:10:09.280
been very good for us because that really helped us in the regulatory process because we know the

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:15.479
ins and outs of this package. We know the weaknesses and the strengths. So if the FDA

00:10:15.479 --> 00:10:25.280
ever comes to a door and asks us questions about this package, it will be very easy for us to

00:10:26.200 --> 00:10:32.559
provide them with answers. Another thing that this package does is because we have to support

00:10:32.559 --> 00:10:42.000
not just one model, but we support over 100 pharmacology models, the PKPDSim package can

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:53.760
actually generate new packages based on specifications that you provide. So you write

00:10:53.760 --> 00:11:02.200
a spec file where you describe the drug and you describe the equations for that specific model.

00:11:02.200 --> 00:11:10.880
That will be then put into a package example. And then that will be compiled, validated,

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:17.280
and deployed. And the benefits of this is that it makes it a lot easier and faster to develop

00:11:17.400 --> 00:11:25.159
these models and also to maintain it and also to create the end user documentation for all

00:11:25.159 --> 00:11:29.200
these models because that's also something that we have to provide to the clinician or to the

00:11:29.200 --> 00:11:38.520
pharmacist. So then a little bit about the architecture. Well, we're speaking at an R

00:11:38.679 --> 00:11:49.039
conference and we're speaking about web applications. So the elephant in the room

00:11:49.039 --> 00:12:02.679
that we have to address is Shiny. And of course, I think it's fine to write a medical device in

00:12:02.799 --> 00:12:17.080
Shiny. There's absolutely no objection to that. And if you're worried about the scalability of

00:12:17.080 --> 00:12:27.200
that, you can always split off the API so that it scales independently from the web application. So

00:12:27.200 --> 00:12:32.080
that's completely fine. But really early on, we made the decision to not go with Shiny. And

00:12:32.080 --> 00:12:42.840
that was mostly because we thought in the end, the application would be too complex. It would

00:12:42.840 --> 00:12:52.280
be too hard to develop in Shiny. That's why we went with a sort of more default JavaScript stack.

00:12:52.440 --> 00:13:01.960
If we then go into the API itself, which we of course left in R, what you have to keep in mind

00:13:01.960 --> 00:13:10.760
is the scale and the load requirements for the API. Well, we don't have the load requirements

00:13:10.760 --> 00:13:17.640
that were presented before, like a million users a day or a million API calls a day. We have a

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:25.000
little bit less. We are growing, but we have about a few hundred API calls an hour.

00:13:26.039 --> 00:13:34.840
But you do have to keep in mind that it's not always the same over the course of a day.

00:13:36.200 --> 00:13:44.919
We always have a peak in the morning when the users on the East Coast wake up. And what you

00:13:44.919 --> 00:13:50.039
also have to keep in mind is that the length of the API call is not always the same. We have a lot

00:13:50.039 --> 00:13:57.320
of API calls that are really fast, within a second. But there's also API calls that actually

00:13:57.320 --> 00:14:02.760
take much longer, depending on how much information you have for the specific patient.

00:14:05.479 --> 00:14:10.599
So that also leads to the question of what API framework you're going to use. Well,

00:14:10.599 --> 00:14:19.960
when we started out about five years ago, the first API framework that we built was our own.

00:14:22.599 --> 00:14:30.760
But we quickly realized that a great application already existed,

00:14:30.760 --> 00:14:35.960
and that was called OpenCPU, which basically exposes our

00:14:40.119 --> 00:14:49.880
packages as an API. And that has worked really well for us. And we initially put that just on

00:14:49.880 --> 00:15:03.080
a server in the cloud, but later we moved it to a dockerized version, so it would scale more

00:15:03.080 --> 00:15:07.000
easily up and down, depending on the load. And that has worked really well for us.

00:15:08.119 --> 00:15:12.840
Of course, at this meeting, there's been a lot of talk already about Plumber. We are looking into

00:15:12.840 --> 00:15:19.799
it. It has a few nice things that it can do, but there will be something for the future.

00:15:20.440 --> 00:15:25.559
We might move to that. Another thing here that would be good to mention is maybe

00:15:28.039 --> 00:15:36.119
Lambdas on Amazon, which basically allows you to upload a specific function, and then

00:15:36.919 --> 00:15:45.880
you can easily use that function, and you don't have to worry about the scaling at all. So that's

00:15:45.880 --> 00:15:52.840
another option that we might look into. And I also know that there's a lot of other folks that are

00:15:52.840 --> 00:15:59.159
working on API frameworks, but I don't have the time to go into that. So to round off, I think

00:15:59.400 --> 00:16:04.359
I think, yeah, the main question medical devices are, if there was a

00:16:06.599 --> 00:16:17.239
question mark in anyone's mind, I think, yes, it's not a problem. There's no regulatory

00:16:17.239 --> 00:16:22.200
requirement that actually says you have to develop your tool in a specific language.

00:16:22.760 --> 00:16:24.359
A functional

00:16:31.080 --> 00:16:35.559
testing is really important. Remember all those requirements that you have to go through.

00:16:37.080 --> 00:16:45.159
And what really helped us, I think, to actually do that, to develop that at scale is store as much

00:16:45.239 --> 00:16:53.080
in the metadata as you can. That also really helped us with maintaining all these models

00:16:54.520 --> 00:17:01.799
as well. And then the last thing that I briefly mentioned is that, in my opinion, it really helped

00:17:03.559 --> 00:17:10.359
that we at least the crucial code for our medical device that we had to write it ourselves,

00:17:10.359 --> 00:17:14.280
so we know exactly what's going on under the hood.

00:17:15.319 --> 00:17:19.880
Well, thank you for your attention, and I'd be happy to ask some questions.

00:17:28.280 --> 00:17:35.640
So we have a couple of questions, mostly on the clinical side. So how does this functionality

00:17:35.640 --> 00:17:41.239
integrate into the clinical workflow, and does it integrate into an EHR?

00:17:41.239 --> 00:17:49.959
Yeah, that's a great one. Yes, we do integrate with all the major EHR vendors, like Epic and

00:17:49.959 --> 00:18:00.760
Cerner. And the way it usually works is the pharmacist or the doctor is actually working

00:18:00.760 --> 00:18:06.760
on a patient in their main workflow, and then they can click a button to get advice from us.

00:18:08.040 --> 00:18:22.199
And that basically brings up our web application. And then in our view, so all the specific data

00:18:22.199 --> 00:18:27.640
that we need is already there. So the user only has to look at our screen and make a

00:18:31.719 --> 00:18:36.119
decision about the dose, so they don't actually have to enter any more data.

00:18:36.119 --> 00:18:38.439
Thank you. And does...

00:18:42.760 --> 00:18:52.599
Let's see. How about domain knowledge in the development process? Do you have pharmacists

00:18:52.599 --> 00:18:54.839
on your team? Yes, I'm a pharmacist,

00:18:55.800 --> 00:19:02.680
but I'm also a researcher and a developer, so I have more than one hat. But we do now have

00:19:04.280 --> 00:19:10.359
three pharmacists on staff as well to help with development, because they actually know

00:19:11.239 --> 00:19:16.040
what's important to actually show to the user. They help a lot out with the support as well.

00:19:16.680 --> 00:19:25.479
So is the device effective across classes of drugs like oncological or psychotropic drugs?

00:19:25.479 --> 00:19:32.520
Yeah, we have a few modules in oncology. I would say most of our modules are in

00:19:34.119 --> 00:19:40.119
infectious diseases, because that's where the most need is. But we are looking into

00:19:40.119 --> 00:19:44.439
a lot of other classes as well. So thank you so much. So please thank our speaker.

00:19:46.040 --> 00:19:48.839
Thank you.

